ALEKH2D — FLOW: CV-BASED ADAPTIVE REGION CROPPING
====================================================

GOAL
----
Only send the LLM images of areas that actually contain content
(components, dimensions, title block). Skip blank space entirely.
This is the lowest token-cost option since no wasted tiles are sent.


STEP 1 — RENDER MASTER IMAGE
-----------------------------
- Input: user-uploaded PDF (single or multi-page GA/assembly drawing).
- Use pypdfium2 to render each page at high DPI (e.g. scale=3.0-4.0).
- This becomes the "master image" — the coordinate reference frame
  for every crop and every bbox returned later.
- Keep this master image in memory; do NOT send it to the LLM directly
  at high detail (too expensive, too low-res for small labels anyway).


STEP 2 — TITLE BLOCK REGION (fixed or detected)
-------------------------------------------------
- Title blocks sit in a predictable spot on Tata Steel templates
  (bottom-right corner).
- Option A (fast): fixed-percentage crop, e.g. bottom-right 30% width
  x 20% height, cropped from the master image at full resolution.
- Option B (robust): use Tesseract OCR to search the page for known
  label strings ("DRG.No.", "REV", "TATA STEEL", "SHEET NO.") and use
  their bounding boxes to locate and crop the title block region.
- Once cropped, either:
    (a) run local OCR (Tesseract) directly on the crop and skip the
        LLM entirely for structured fields like DRG.No, REV, DATE,
        MATERIAL, SCALE, SHEET NO — these are clean printed text and
        don't need vision reasoning.
    (b) OR send the small crop to the LLM only if OCR confidence is
        low or fields are handwritten/stamped.
- This step costs $0 in the common case (OCR-only).


STEP 3 — CV-BASED CONTENT REGION DETECTION
---------------------------------------------
- Convert master image to grayscale, apply Otsu thresholding to binarize.
- Apply morphological dilation (small kernel) to merge nearby ink
  (individual characters/lines) into connected blobs — this turns
  "TRUCK DUMP HOPPER" from scattered letters into one connected region.
- Run cv2.findContours (or MSER) on the dilated binary image to get a
  list of bounding boxes for all connected ink regions.
- Filter out:
    - Very small contours (noise, dots, stray marks)
    - The already-handled title block region (step 2)
    - Very large contours that just outline the whole page border
- Optionally merge overlapping/adjacent contours into larger unified
  regions (e.g. group anything within N pixels of each other) so you
  don't end up with hundreds of tiny separate crops.
- Output: a list of candidate region bounding boxes in master-image
  coordinates — e.g. [elevation view, plan view, key plan, legend,
  hopper detail cluster, pulley detail cluster, ...].


STEP 4 — CROP + (OPTIONAL) COMPOSITE
---------------------------------------
- For each candidate region: crop from the master image with small
  padding (10-20px) so nothing gets clipped at the edge.
- If a region is still very large/dense (e.g. the whole elevation
  view spans thousands of pixels), optionally sub-tile only that
  region using a small internal sliding window (bounded, not
  page-wide) — this is the only place tiling logic is used, and only
  when truly necessary.
- Cost-saving option: instead of sending each region crop as a
  separate image, stitch multiple smaller crops into a single
  labeled composite image (grid layout, clear borders, cell labels)
  using PIL. One well-labeled composite costs less than N separate
  images.


STEP 5 — SINGLE LLM CALL PER PAGE
------------------------------------
- Build one prompt_content list (as already done in extract_data):
    - system_instruction (unified schema: dimension rows AND
      component rows, per Category field)
    - title block crop image (only if OCR was low-confidence)
    - each region crop / composite image, "detail": "high"
    - do NOT include the full master image at high detail
- Send everything in one call_llm() invocation — no extra round trips.


STEP 6 — MERGE, DEDUPE, NORMALIZE
------------------------------------
- Parse LLM response via extract_json_array (already exists).
- If overlap padding caused any duplicate detections across adjacent
  region crops, dedupe by fuzzy text match on Dim_Description /
  Component_Name, or by bbox proximity once bboxes are converted back
  to master-image coordinates (add crop offset to each local bbox).
- Feed into existing BigQuery logging, Excel export, and Fabric.js
  canvas rendering — no changes needed downstream.


COST PROFILE
-------------
- Cheapest of all approaches (adaptive crops, sliding window,
  single full-page image).
- No wasted tokens on blank space.
- No overlap waste (only pads regions slightly, doesn't duplicate
  whole tiles).
- Title block often costs $0 (OCR only, no LLM).


DEPENDENCIES NEEDED
---------------------
- pypdfium2 (already in use) — page rendering
- opencv-python (new) — contour detection, morphological ops
- pytesseract (already a dependency from the Tata Steel indent
  project) — title block OCR, optional label-based region detection
- PIL/Pillow (already in use) — cropping, compositing
